{"parentUuid":"ed37692f-3b87-4387-a228-aa0490a67ff9","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012Y6JhhcSEp2DDUVc95r2uM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants to:\n1. Use LangGraph with a multi-node approach (UX Researcher node + Critic node)\n2. Use Gemini's native video understanding\n3. Model: `gemini-3-flash-preview` (though I should verify this - the spec says \"Gemini 3.0 Flash\" but the actual model ID might be different)\n\nLet me think about the architecture before starting:\n\n**Architecture:**\n- Next.js frontend with TypeScript\n- File upload component for videos\n- API routes to handle video processing\n- LangGraph for orchestration with two nodes:\n  - Node 1: \"UX Researcher\" - analyzes the video and identifies UX issues\n  - Node 2: \"Critic\" - validates which issues are actual bugs vs stylistic choices\n- Gemini native video understanding (upload video to Gemini Files API, then analyze)\n\n**Tech Stack Details:**\n- Next.js 14+ (App Router)\n- TypeScript\n- `@langchain/langgraph` for the graph\n- `@google/generative-ai` or `@langchain/google-genai` for Gemini integration\n- Gemini Files API for video upload\n- Video playback in the frontend\n\n**LangGraph Flow:**\n1. User uploads video through the frontend\n2. Video gets sent to the backend API route\n3. Backend uploads video to Gemini Files API and gets a file reference\n4. LangGraph orchestrates the analysis: UX Researcher node analyzes the video for issues, then Critic node validates the findings\n5. Results returned to frontend for display\n\n**Frontend:**\n- Video upload UI\n- Video player (native HTML5 or a React component)\n- Analysis results panel showing:\n  - Issues categorized by type\n  - Severity\n  - Critic's verdict (bug vs stylistic)\n  - Recommendations\n\nI need to verify the correct Gemini model ID—the user mentioned `gemini-3-flash-preview` but I should double-check against Google's current model 