{"parentUuid":"20656b04-eb5e-4fda-bdaa-74fae22f6385","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KXWgWPq3sbDkn1tpwoUYNv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information I need. Let me build the complete Video UX Analyzer application. Let me plan the full implementation:\n\n**Architecture:**\n- Next.js 15 + TypeScript + Tailwind CSS\n- LangGraph with Researcher → Critic nodes\n- Gemini native video understanding via Files API\n- SSE streaming for real-time progress updates\n\n**Key technical decisions from the docs:**\n1. `fileManager.uploadFile(buffer, { mimeType, displayName })` - supports Buffer directly\n2. `Annotation.Root` with reducers for arrays\n3. Nodes return `Partial<AppState>`\n\n\n4. System instructions for better prompts\n\nThe LangGraph flow moves from researcher to critic, and I'm setting up the state annotation with video metadata, arrays for findings and validated issues with appropriate reducers, and fields for the overall assessment...\n\nDefining the state schema...\n\nFor `researcherFindings`, since the researcher returns all findings at once rather than appending incrementally, I should use a replacement reducer that takes the full list from the right side instead of concatenating. Same logic applies to `validatedIssues` — both nodes return complete results, so replacement makes more sense than accumulation.\n\nNow I'm sketching out the project structure with the API route, components, and LangGraph modules organized in the src directory.\n\nFor the API endpoint, I need to handle multipart form data to extract the video buffer, then stream SSE events back to the client as the analysis progresses through uploading, processing, researching, and critiquing stages. Since Next.js App Router handles `request.formData()` natively, I don't need external body parsing middleware.\n\nFor the file size limit, I should configure it in the route handler itself using the `config` export, setting a reasonable limit like 200mb for the trial while noting this would need adjustment for production use. Setting up the project dependencies...\n\nNow I'm configuring the Next.js setup to handle larger file uploads by increasing the server action body size limit to 200MB, and defining the TypeScript configuration for the application structure.\n\nDefining the core data structures... Setting up the state annotations for the graph with fields for the video, researcher findings, validated issues, overall assessment, and error handling. Now I'm defining the researcher node that uses the Gemini API with a system prompt for a senior UX researcher persona.\n\nDefining the prompt structure... I'm setting up the researcher node by initializing the Gemini model with the system instructions, then sending the video file and prompt to generate UX findings, parsing the JSON response to extract the issues, and handling any errors that occur during the process.\n\nNow I'm moving to the critic node, which takes those researcher findings and evaluates each one to determine whether it's a genuine usability bug, an intentional design choice, or something that needs further investigation. I'm setting up the critic node function that takes the researcher's findings, sends them to the Gemini model with a system prompt, parses the JSON response to extract validated issues and an overall assessment, and returns those results to update the application state.\n\nNow I'm building the workflow graph using LangGraph, connecting the researcher node to the critic node in sequence, starting from the researcher and ending after the critic completes.\n\nSetting up file upload utilities...\n\nConfiguring the API route... Writing the streaming response...\n\nI'm noticing a timing issue where the graph completes its full analysis synchronously, but I'm sending UI stage updates as if they're happening sequentially—the \"critiquing\" message goes out after the graph has already finished running both the researcher and critic internally.\n\nI could manually invoke each node separately to get proper timing, but that would bypass the LangGraph structure entirely. Since the assignment emphasizes using LangGraph, I'll accept this minor UI inconsistency rather than work around the framework.\n\nWait—LangGraph actually has streaming built in. I can use the `.stream()` method with `streamMode: \"updates\"` to emit events as each node completes, which lets me send real-time SSE updates tied to actual node execution. This is the proper architectural approach and shows correct LangGraph usage.\n\nSetting up the API route to leverage this streaming pattern...\n\nHandling the stream updates...\n\nI'm realizing that with `streamMode: \"updates\"`, each chunk contains only the state changes from that node, not the full state. The critic node won't have access to the researcher findings since it doesn't return them. I could either stream for progress updates and then call `graph.invoke()` separately to get the complete final state, or switch to `streamMode: \"values\"` to get the full state after each node runs.\n\nLet me go with a hybrid approach: stream the updates to track progress, then reconstruct the final state by merging all the updates together. I'll iterate through the stream, accumulate the state changes, and emit progress events as each node completes.\n\nNow I'm setting up the full API route...\n\nI'm handling the incoming video file, converting it to a buffer, and uploading it to Gemini while streaming status updates back to the client. Once the video is processed, I'm initializing the state with the video URI and preparing to run it through the analysis graph.\n\nNow I'm iterating through the graph stream updates, merging each node's output into the collected state and checking for researcher findings to report progress back to the client. Writing the frontend components... Setting up the component state with refs for the video file, URL, and processing stages, then defining handlers for file selection and the analysis workflow that uploads the video and manages the UI state through each processing phase. Building the UI layout... Writing the VideoUploader component... Writing the upload UI... Writing the video player and controls...\n\nI'm realizing the reset button approach is clunky with that File hack. Better to add an `onReset` prop that the parent can handle cleanly. Now I'm thinking through the AnalysisResults component structure—it needs to handle multiple states as the analysis progresses: idle state with a prompt, then uploading and processing steps with spinners, followed by the UX research and critique phases, and finally displaying the complete results. I'll organize it around these distinct stages so the UI can smoothly transition through each one. Defining the verdict and severity configurations...\n\nNow I'm setting up the category mappings for different issue types. Time to stop planning and actually write out all these configuration files—I'll set up the directory structure and create the globals stylesheet with Tailwind directives, the Next.js layout with proper metadata, and the Tailwind and PostCSS configs.\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a potential issue: `state.ts` needs to import `Annotation` from `@langchain/langgraph`, which is a runtime dependency, not just a type. If client components try to import from `state.ts`, they'll pull in server-side code that won't work in the browser. I need to be careful about how I structure these imports to keep the type definitions separate from the runtime dependencies.\n\nThe cleanest solution is to split this into two files: one with pure TypeScript types that both client and server can safely import, and another server-only file that handles the LangGraph-specific state definition with its runtime imports. That way client components can reference the types without dragging in unnecessary server code.\n\nNow I'm laying out all the files I need to create for this project, starting with the configuration files and working through the app structure, API routes, shared types, LangGraph setup, and React components.\n\nFor the Tailwind and TypeScript configs, I need to make sure the paths are set up correctly to reference my source files and enable proper module resolution with Next.js.\n\nI'm thinking through the component architecture—specifically how to handle the video upload flow and reset mechanism properly, using state management to track the file, its preview URL, and a key to force component remounting when the user wants to start over.\n\nWriting the page component and uploader logic...\n\nNow I need to make sure the NOTES.md file is comprehensive and well-structured since that's what the reviewer will evaluate—it should explain the overall architecture, walk through how to run the project, and give a clear picture of how all the pieces fit together.\n\nI'm also working through the graph streaming pattern with LangGraph. The key thing is that `graph.stream()` returns an async generator directly, so I iterate through it with `for await` without needing an extra await. Each chunk that comes through will have the node name as a key with its output data nested inside.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the implementation details—handling different video MIME types since browsers might report MOV files as `video/quicktime`, and I'll just pass the file type directly to the Gemini API. For the progress indicator, I need to map out which steps are active, complete, or pending based on the current stage as it moves from uploading through processing, researching, and critiquing to completion.\n\nWriting step status logic... I'm settling on a simpler approach—just hardcoding the step status logic directly in the component rather than trying to abstract it further. Now I need to handle the API route carefully, making sure the async generator from `graph.stream()` completes properly within the ReadableStream controller before the connection closes.\n\nSetting up the stream controller... Setting up state variables to accumulate the researcher findings and validated issues as they stream in, then extracting and enqueuing each stage's results with appropriate progress messages.\n\nNow I'm planning how to write out all the remaining files efficiently—I can batch them into groups by category like config files, type definitions, and components to keep the parallel writes manageable. I'm settling on a dark theme with `gray-950` as the background and `violet-600` for accents, using Tailwind v3.4+. For the issue cards, I'll keep the design simple and flat—each card will have a subtle border, hover effects, a verdict badge in the corner, category and severity indicators at the bottom, and the critic's reasoning displayed inline without any collapsing. Now I'm visualizing the two-column layout with the video uploader on the left and analysis results on the right, where results show either progress steps during analysis or the final assessment once complete.\n\nThe issue cards themselves will display in a sorted list by severity, with each card showing the navigation marker, issue description, timestamp, and the critic's take. I'm ready to start writing the actual implementation now.\n\nDefining the TypeScript types...\n\nNow I need to configure Next.js to handle large file uploads properly, and I'm checking what the body size limit settings are for the App Router. body size limit via the `serverExternalPackages` or directly in the route config. For large files, the recommended approach is streaming, but for simplicity, I'll set a higher limit and note this in NOTES.md.\n\nFor API routes, Next.js uses the Node.js HTTP server, which by default doesn't have a body size limit. The `maxDuration` export controls how long the route can run. The actual body size depends on available memory.\n\nThe key configuration for serverless environments (like Vercel) is setting `maxDuration` to 300 seconds for a 5-minute timeout. There's no direct API route body size config in the App Router, and Vercel's platform limits are 4.5MB for serverless functions, though local dev or self-hosted setups should handle larger payloads fine. I'll document this in NOTES.md.\n\nNow for the `researcher.ts` prompt parsing, I need to handle different JSON response formats from Gemini. The parser needs to account for pure JSON arrays, JSON wrapped in markdown code blocks, and JSON mixed with explanatory text. I'm building a more robust extraction function that tries to match JSON structures first, then falls back to stripping markdown formatting if needed. Now I'm settling on the package versions—going with the latest stable releases across Next.js, React, the Google Generative AI SDK, LangGraph, and Zod, along with their corresponding type definitions and build tools.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether to include Zod for validating Gemini's JSON responses—it would be more robust, but I'll keep things simpler for now with direct JSON parsing and error handling instead. With that decision locked in, I'm ready to start writing out all the files.\n\nOne thing I need to clarify: when calling `Annotation<string>()` without options, it defaults to a \"last write wins\" reducer. For fields like `videoUri` and `videoMimeType` that get set once and never change, that simple replacement behavior works fine.\n\nFor `researcherFindings`, the critic node reads what the researcher sets, so I'll use an explicit reducer that takes the right value with an empty array default. Same pattern applies to `validatedIssues` and `overallAssessment`—both set once by the critic node. The `error` field follows the same approach if any node fails.\n\nNow I'm writing the files in priority order: configuration and types first, then the LangGraph implementation, API route, UI components, and documentation. I'll also make sure the system prompts for the researcher and critic personas are really strong.\n\nThe researcher should embody someone with deep UX research expertise who can spot friction points and usability issues from a user's perspective. The critic needs to be someone who understands that not every rough edge is a problem—they validate findings and separate genuine issues from intentional design choices, then prioritize what matters most.\n\nLet me start writing all the files now.\n\nActually, I need to think through the streaming architecture first. When the graph processes, the researcher node completes before the critic starts, so I need to make sure the SSE events fire at the right moments—\"researching\" before the graph starts, \"critiquing\" after the researcher finishes, and \"complete\" after the critic finishes. The tricky part is that sending \"researching\" before `graph.stream()` starts might create a false sense of timing since there could be queuing delays, but that's fine for setting user expectations. Now I'm mapping out the actual timeline: the upload stage fires immediately, then the video upload takes 10-60 seconds, then processing begins. The flow is actually working correctly—`processing` fires when we start the upload, `researching` kicks in after the upload completes and before the graph begins streaming, then `critiquing` and `complete` fire as each stage of the analysis finishes. Now I'm ready to write out all the final files.\n\nWriting configuration and source files...\n\nNow I'm laying out the VideoUploader component with a drag-drop zone for videos, a player preview, and buttons to start analysis or select a different file. For AnalysisResults, I'm building a multi-state display that shows instructions when idle, a progress indicator while analyzing, error messaging on failure, and a detailed breakdown of issues when complete—with stats, an overall assessment, and individual issue cards sorted by severity with verdicts, categories, and critic notes.\n\nI'm structuring the page with a dark slate background, a bordered header with backdrop blur, and a centered grid layout that splits into two columns on larger screens. The issue cards display the category and verdict badges at the top, the problem description in the middle, a timestamp chip, and the critic's reasoning in italics at the bottom.\n\nNow I need to handle the case where the Gemini API returns slightly malformed JSON. I'm writing a utility function that strips markdown code blocks and uses regex to extract either a JSON array or object from the response text, then parses it safely.\n\nWriting JSON extraction logic...\n\nFor the styling, I'm planning to use Tailwind's color palette for a dark theme—slate-950 for the background, slate-900 and slate-800 for surfaces, with violet-500 as the accent color and various slate grays for text hierarchy.\n\nI also need to set up the status colors: red for genuine bugs and critical issues, sky blue for stylistic choices, amber for items needing investigation, and orange/yellow for major and minor severity levels.\n\nNow I'm configuring the Next.js 15 setup with the proper TypeScript format and turbopack support...\n\nI'll handle the body size limit by noting in the documentation that production deployments should use presigned URLs for video uploads directly to cloud storage, since the App Router doesn't have a straightforward way to configure this locally.\n\nTime to start writing the code in batches—first the configuration files and type definitions, then the core components and utilities, and finally the API routes and pages. be more efficient than sending them sequentially. I'll group the file writes into a few parallel batches to keep things manageable while still moving quickly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12607,"cache_read_input_tokens":18426,"output_tokens":17941,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tok