{"parentUuid":"bc4d2986-e212-45b6-bc09-689fdd3d33d4","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"d3617822-df31-4211-9ed4-8dcd9155784c","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XSAznxMxnTmxTsLZv7nNgv","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /home/akshay/projects/video_ux_analyzer/NOTES.md (file state is current in your context — no need to Read it back)"}]},"uuid":"046869ad-b6ac-4db3-ab78-70017001bfa8","timestamp":"2026-04-22T11:23:34.780Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"create","filePath":"/home/akshay/projects/video_ux_analyzer/NOTES.md","content":"# Video UX Analyzer — Notes\n\n## High-Level Design\n\n```\nBrowser\n  │\n  │  FormData (video file)\n  ▼\nNext.js API Route (/api/analyze)\n  │\n  │  SSE stream (stage updates + final results)\n  │\n  ├── 1. uploadVideoToGemini()\n  │       └── GoogleAIFileManager.uploadFile(buffer)\n  │           Poll until FileState.ACTIVE\n  │\n  └── 2. LangGraph (graph.stream, streamMode: \"updates\")\n          │\n          ├── Node: researcher\n          │     └── gemini-3-flash-preview + video URI\n          │         System: Senior UX Researcher persona\n          │         Output: UXIssue[] (JSON)\n          │\n          └── Node: critic\n                └── gemini-3-flash-preview + researcher findings\n                    System: VP of Design persona\n                    Output: ValidatedIssue[] + overallAssessment (JSON)\n```\n\n### Why LangGraph?\nUX analysis is inherently subjective. A single LLM pass tends to over-report every rough edge as a critical bug. The two-node graph separates concerns:\n\n- **Researcher node** simulates an evidence-based UX researcher mentally walking through the product as a first-time user.\n- **Critic node** acts as a design director who knows that not everything is a bug — some patterns are intentional brand or platform choices. It validates each finding, classifying it as a `genuine_bug`, `stylistic_choice`, or `needs_investigation`.\n\nThis produces a more credible, actionable output compared to a single prompt.\n\n### LangGraph State\nState uses `Annotation.Root` with explicit reducers. Both `researcherFindings` and `validatedIssues` use replacement reducers (`(_, right) => right`) since each node produces its full output in a single call. The graph streams node-level updates, allowing the API route to send progress SSE events as each node completes.\n\n### Real-time Feedback (SSE)\nThe API route uses a `ReadableStream` to emit Server-Sent Events throughout the pipeline:\n1. `uploading` → receiving file\n2. `processing` → Gemini Files API upload + polling\n3. `researching` → researcher node running\n4. `critiquing` → critic node running (fires when researcher completes)\n5. `complete` → full results payload\n\nThe frontend reads the SSE stream via `fetch` + `ReadableStream` reader, updating the progress stepper in real time.\n\n---\n\n## How to Run\n\n### Prerequisites\n- Node.js 18+\n- A Google Gemini API key (get one from [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com))\n\n### Setup\n\n```bash\ncd video_ux_analyzer\n\n# Install dependencies\nnpm install\n\n# Create your env file\ncp .env.local.example .env.local\n# Edit .env.local and add your GEMINI_API_KEY\n\n# Start the dev server\nnpm run dev\n```\n\nOpen [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000), upload a product demo video (MP4/MOV/WebM), and click **Analyze UX**.\n\n---\n\n## Production Concerns\n\n### 1. Video Upload Size & Latency\nThe current implementation uploads the video through the Next.js server (browser → Next.js → Gemini). This doubles bandwidth and hits serverless function body size limits (~4.5MB on Vercel).\n\n**Fix:** Generate a short-lived upload token server-side and have the browser upload directly to Gemini's Files API (or to an intermediary bucket like S3 with a presigned URL, then trigger processing via a background job).\n\n### 2. Serverless Timeout\nGemini video processing + two LLM calls can easily exceed 60-90 seconds for longer videos. Vercel serverless functions have a 60s default timeout (300s on Pro).\n\n**Fix:** Move processing to a background queue (e.g., BullMQ, Inngest, or a long-running container). Return a job ID immediately, poll for results, and notify via WebSocket or push notification when done.\n\n### 3. Gemini File Retention\nFiles uploaded to the Gemini Files API are automatically deleted after 48 hours. For any kind of history or re-analysis feature, the video must be stored elsewhere (e.g., S3) and re-uploaded on demand.\n\n### 4. JSON Parsing Brittleness\nBoth nodes ask Gemini to return raw JSON and use regex extraction + `JSON.parse`. Under load or with unusual video content, the model may produce malformed output.\n\n**Fix:** Use Gemini's native structured output (response schema / function calling) to enforce a JSON schema at the API level, eliminating the need for string parsing entirely.\n\n### 5. No Auth or Rate Limiting\nThe `/api/analyze` endpoint is open. Each request consumes Gemini API quota and can be expensive.\n\n**Fix:** Add authentication (NextAuth / Clerk) and per-user rate limiting (e.g., Upstash Redis).\n\n### 6. Error Recovery in the Graph\nIf the researcher node succeeds but the critic node fails, the whole analysis is lost. \n\n**Fix:** Persist intermediate node outputs (e.g., to Redis or a database keyed by job ID) so that a critic retry can resume from the saved researcher findings without re-processing the video.\n\n### 7. Prompt Versioning\nPrompts are hardcoded in the node files. Changes to prompts in production would require a deployment.\n\n**Fix:** Store prompts in a database or CMS with versioning, enabling A/B testing of researcher vs. critic personas without code deploys.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"bc4d2986-e212-45b6-bc09-689fdd3d33d4","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"/home/akshay/projects/video_ux_analyzer","sessionId":"43aa6f4e-238a-49ff-bcee-676bf9b5ead2","version":"2.1.111","gitBranch":"HEAD"}
