ance, demonstrates the user flow end-to-end.\n","structuredPatch":[{"oldStart":1,"oldLines":113,"newStart":1,"newLines":173,"lines":[" # Video UX Analyzer — Notes"," ","+A Next.js + LangGraph + Gemini app that analyzes product demo videos for UX issues. A two-stage AI pipeline (UX Researcher → parallel Critic validators → Synthesizer) streams findings progressively to a polished light-theme UI inspired by the Twisty dashboard reference.","+","+---","+"," ## High-Level Design"," "," ```"," Browser","-  │","   │  FormData (video file)","   ▼"," Next.js API Route (/api/analyze)","+  │  SSE stream (stage updates + per-issue events)","   │","-  │  SSE stream (stage updates + final results)","-  │","   ├── 1. uploadVideoToGemini()","-  │       └── GoogleAIFileManager.uploadFile(buffer)","+  │       └── Buffer → temp file → GoogleAIFileManager.uploadFile()","   │           Poll until FileState.ACTIVE","   │","   └── 2. LangGraph (graph.stream, streamMode: \"updates\")","           │","           ├── Node: researcher","-          │     └── gemini-3-flash-preview + video URI","-          │         System: Senior UX Researcher persona","-          │         Output: UXIssue[] (JSON)","+          │     └── gemini-2.5-flash + video URI","+          │         System prompt: \"Senior UX Researcher at NN/g\"","+          │         Output: UXIssue[] (JSON, one batch)","           │","-          └── Node: critic","-                └── gemini-3-flash-preview + researcher findings","-                    System: VP of Design persona","-                    Output: ValidatedIssue[] + overallAssessment (JSON)","+          ├── Send fan-out — one critic invocation per finding","+          │","+          ├── Node: critic × N (parallel)","+          │     └── gemini-2.5-flash + single issue","+          │         System prompt: \"VP of Design\"","+          │         Output: ValidatedIssue (verdict + reasoning)","+          │     Reducer: validatedIssues = [...left, ...right]  // append","+          │","+          └── Node: synthesizer (barrier, runs once after all critics)","+                └── gemini-2.5-flash + all validated issues","+                    Output: overallAssessment (plain text)"," ```"," ","-### Why LangGraph?","-UX analysis is inherently subjective. A single LLM pass tends to over-report every rough edge as a critical bug. The two-node graph separates concerns:","+### Why LangGraph (and why this shape)"," ","-- **Researcher node** simulates an evidence-based UX researcher mentally walking through the product as a first-time user.","-- **Critic node** acts as a design director who knows that not everything is a bug — some patterns are intentional brand or platform choices. It validates each finding, classifying it as a `genuine_bug`, `stylistic_choice`, or `needs_investigation`.","+UX feedback is subjective. A single LLM pass over-reports rough edges as critical bugs. The graph separates concerns:"," ","-This produces a more credible, actionable output compared to a single prompt.","+- **Researcher** simulates a first-time user mentally walking through the demo, returns *all* findings in one batch.","+- **Critic** (fan-out) evaluates *each* finding independently — `genuine_bug` / `stylistic_choice` / `needs_investigation`. Running them in parallel via `Send` is faster and keeps each critic call focused on one finding.","+- **Synthesizer** is a barrier — LangGraph waits for all critic invocations to converge before producing the executive summary."," ","-### LangGraph State","-State uses `Annotation.Root` with explicit reducers. Both `researcherFindings` and `validatedIssues` use replacement reducers (`(_, right) => right`) since each node produces its full output in a single call. The graph streams node-level updates, allowing the API route to send progress SSE events as each node completes.","+State uses `Annotation.Root` with explicit reducers — `validatedIssues` uses an append reducer so parallel critic outputs merge correctly into the parent state."," ","-### Real-time Feedback (SSE)","-The API route uses a `ReadableStream` to emit Server-Sent Events throughout the pipeline:","-1. `uploading` → receiving file","-2. `processing` → Gemini Files API upload + polling","-3. `researching` → researcher node running","-4. `critiquing` → critic node running (fires when researcher completes)","-5. `complete` → full results payload","+### Real-time UX (SSE)"," ","-The frontend reads the SSE stream via `fetch` + `ReadableStream` reader, updating the progress stepper in real time.","+The API route consumes `graph.stream(..., { streamMode: \"updates\" })` and emits Server-Sent Events as each node completes:"," ","+| Stage | Trigger | Frontend behavior |","+| --- | --- | --- |","+| `uploading` | Form data received | Spinner |","+| `processing` | Uploading + polling Gemini Files API | Spinner |","+| `researching` | Researcher node started | Stepper highlights research |","+| `validating` (researcher_complete) | Researcher returned N findings | Skeleton cards render with shimmer for each finding |","+| `validating` (issue_validated × N) | Each critic completes | Skeleton swaps to validated card with verdict; stat counters tick up |","+| `synthesizing` | All critics done, synthesizer running | Spinner |","+| `complete` | Synthesizer returned overall assessment | Gradient assessment card fades in |","+","+The user never stares at a blank loading screen — content materializes progressively.","+","+### Frontend stack","+","+- Next.js 15 (App Router) + TypeScript","+- Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui (Dialog, Tabs, Button) backed by Radix primitives","+- Light theme tuned to match a Twisty-style dashboard: white cards on a soft off-white background, generous radii, soft pastel pill colors, large stat numbers, gradient Overall Assessment card","+- Lucide icons throughout","+- Per-category icon chips (Compass / MousePointer2 / Workflow / Accessibility / Clock / MessageSquare) for visual scanability","+","+### Key features","+","+- **Drag-drop video upload** with native HTML5 player","+- **Live progress stepper** (4 phases) with stage-specific messaging","+- **Skeleton-fill cards** — researcher findings render immediately, then each card swaps to the validated version as the critic resolves it","+- **Timestamp video sync** — clicking a timestamp on any issue card seeks the video player to that moment and plays","+- **Jira ticket modal** (shadcn Dialog) with two tabs:","+  - *Details* — Summary, Issue Type, dynamic-color Priority badge, Labels (chip input), Description (Jira wiki markup pre-filled), Reporter/Assignee","+  - *Attachments* — Mock video-snippet clipper centered on the issue's timestamp (UI scaffolds the eventual real feature)","+- **URL-template Jira creation** — opens `/secure/CreateIssueDetails!init.jspa?pid=…&issuetype=…&summary=…&description=…&priority=…&labels=…` in a new tab; configurable via `NEXT_PUBLIC_JIRA_BASE_URL` and `NEXT_PUBLIC_JIRA_PROJECT_ID`","+- **Severity / Verdict mapping** — defaults are editable in the modal (critical→Highest, genuine_bug→Bug, etc.)","+"," ---"," "," ## How to Run"," "," ### Prerequisites"," - Node.js 18+","-- A Google Gemini API key (get one from [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com))","+- A Google Gemini API key — [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com)"," "," ### Setup"," "," ```bash"," cd video_ux_analyzer"," ","-# Install dependencies"," npm install"," ","-# Create your env file"," cp .env.local.example .env.local","-# Edit .env.local and add your GEMINI_API_KEY","+# edit .env.local — add GEMINI_API_KEY (required)","+# optionally set NEXT_PUBLIC_JIRA_BASE_URL and NEXT_PUBLIC_JIRA_PROJECT_ID","+#   for the Jira modal's \"Create Issue\" deep-link"," ","-# Start the dev server"," npm run dev"," ```"," ","-Open [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000), upload a product demo video (MP4/MOV/WebM), and click **Analyze UX**.","+Open [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000), drop in a 1–5 min product demo, click **Analyze UX**. Findings stream in within ~30–90 seconds depending on video length."," "," ---"," "," ## Production Concerns"," ","-### 1. Video Upload Size & Latency","-The current implementation uploads the video through the Next.js server (browser → Next.js → Gemini). This doubles bandwidth and hits serverless function body size limits (~4.5MB on Vercel).","+### 1. Video upload size & latency","+Video flows browser → Next.js → Gemini, doubling bandwidth. Vercel serverless has a ~4.5 MB body limit; we set `bodySizeLimit: 200mb` for local dev but that won't survive deployment."," ","-**Fix:** Generate a short-lived upload token server-side and have the browser upload directly to Gemini's Files API (or to an intermediary bucket like S3 with a presigned URL, then trigger processing via a background job).","+**Fix:** Generate a short-lived upload token server-side and have the browser upload directly to Gemini's Files API (or to S3 with a presigned URL, then trigger processing via a background queue)."," ","-### 2. Serverless Timeout","-Gemini video processing + two LLM calls can easily exceed 60-90 seconds for longer videos. Vercel serverless functions have a 60s default timeout (300s on Pro).","+### 2. Serverless timeout","+Gemini video processing + a researcher pass + N parallel critic passes + synthesizer can exceed 60 s for longer videos. Vercel's default is 60 s (300 s on Pro)."," ","-**Fix:** Move processing to a background queue (e.g., BullMQ, Inngest, or a long-running container). Return a job ID immediately, poll for results, and notify via WebSocket or push notification when done.","+**Fix:** Move to a background queue (Inngest, BullMQ, Cloud Tasks). Return a job ID immediately; SSE re-attaches via job ID for resume. Or run on a long-running container."," ","-### 3. Gemini File Retention","-Files uploaded to the Gemini Files API are automatically deleted after 48 hours. For any kind of history or re-analysis feature, the video must be stored elsewhere (e.g., S3) and re-uploaded on demand.","+### 3. Gemini Files API retention","+Files auto-delete after 48 h. Any history / re-analysis feature requires storing the original video elsewhere (S3) and re-uploading."," ","-### 4. JSON Parsing Brittleness","-Both nodes ask Gemini to return raw JSON and use regex extraction + `JSON.parse`. Under load or with unusual video content, the model may produce malformed output.","+### 4. JSON parsing brittleness","+Both nodes ask Gemini for raw JSON and parse with regex + `JSON.parse`. Under unusual content the model may produce malformed output."," ","-**Fix:** Use Gemini's native structured output (response schema / function calling) to enforce a JSON schema at the API level, eliminating the need for string parsing entirely.","+**Fix:** Use Gemini's structured output (response schema / function calling) to enforce JSON at the API level — eliminates string parsing."," ","-### 5. No Auth or Rate Limiting","-The `/api/analyze` endpoint is open. Each request consumes Gemini API quota and can be expensive.","+### 5. No auth or rate limiting","+`/api/analyze` is open. Each request burns Gemini quota and is expensive."," ","-**Fix:** Add authentication (NextAuth / Clerk) and per-user rate limiting (e.g., Upstash Redis).","+**Fix:** Add NextAuth / Clerk + per-user rate limits via Upstash Redis."," ","-### 6. Error Recovery in the Graph","-If the researcher node succeeds but the critic node fails, the whole analysis is lost. ","+### 6. Error recovery in the graph","+A failed critic currently fills in a `needs_investigation` fallback; a failed researcher kills the entire run. There's no resume capability."," ","-**Fix:** Persist intermediate node outputs (e.g., to Redis or a database keyed by job ID) so that a critic retry can resume from the saved researcher findings without re-processing the video.","+**Fix:** Persist node outputs to Redis keyed by job ID so a critic retry resumes from saved researcher findings without re-processing the video."," ","-### 7. Prompt Versioning","-Prompts are hardcoded in the node files. Changes to prompts in production would require a deployment.","+### 7. Prompt versioning","+Prompts and model IDs are hardcoded in node files. Tuning requires a deploy."," ","-**Fix:** Store prompts in a database or CMS with versioning, enabling A/B testing of researcher vs. critic personas without code deploys.","+**Fix:** Store prompts in a database / CMS with versioning + A/B testing.","+","+### 8. Real Jira integration","+The \"Create Issue\" button uses a URL template — the user lands on Jira's create form pre-filled but still has to click Create. A logged-in user with Jira API access expects one-click creation.","+","+**Fix:** Add OAuth → POST to `/rest/api/3/issue`. Map verdict/severity/category to real Jira issue type IDs and priority IDs (currently we send name strings).","+","+### 9. Mock video snippet attachment","+The Attachments tab in the Jira modal is UI-only. Wiring it up requires:","+- Server-side ffmpeg to clip the original video by timestamp range","+- Upload the clip as a Jira attachment via the REST API","+- Show progress / handle failures","+","+### 10. Single-tenant / single-session","+No persistence — refresh loses the analysis. No way to share or revisit results.","+","+**Fix:** Database-backed analysis records keyed by a UUID, shareable URL, optional public/private visibility.","+","+---","+","+## Decisions worth noting","+","+- **Native Gemini video understanding** over frame extraction — Gemini handles temporal context (interaction delays, animations, flow) much better than picking 10 frames.","+- **Two-persona graph** (Researcher + Critic) instead of one prompt — keeps each LLM call focused; the Critic's verdict is the differentiator vs. a generic \"list issues\" tool.","+- **Parallel fan-out (`Send`)** over sequential validation — the researcher returns all findings at once; there's no reason to validate them sequentially. N parallel calls cost the same as N serial calls but finish in ~1× wall time instead of ~N×.","+- **SSE over polling** — analysis is long-running; SSE gives smooth progressive UI without holding a connection-per-issue and without round-trip overhead.","+- **shadcn/ui** for primitives, custom design system for the rest — Dialog/Tabs/Button benefit from Radix accessibility; the rest of the visual language is tuned by hand to match the Twisty reference.","+- **URL-template Jira creation** instead of API integration — zero-config for reviewers, no OAuth dance, demonstrates the user flow end-to-end."]}],"originalFile":"# Video UX Analyzer — Notes\n\n## High-Level Design\n\n```\nBrowser\n  │\n  │  FormData (video file)\n  ▼\nNext.js API Route (/api/analyze)\n  │\n  │  SSE stream (stage updates + final results)\n  │\n  ├── 1. uploadVideoToGemini()\n  │       └── GoogleAIFileManager.uploadFile(buffer)\n  │           Poll until FileState.ACTIVE\n  │\n  └── 2. LangGraph (graph.stream, streamMode: \"updates\")\n          │\n          ├── Node: researcher\n          │     └── gemini-3-flash-preview + video URI\n          │         System: Senior UX Researcher persona\n          │         Output: UXIssue[] (JSON)\n          │\n          └── Node: critic\n                └── gemini-3-flash-preview + researcher findings\n                    System: VP of Design persona\n                    Output: ValidatedIssue[] + overallAssessment (JSON)\n```\n\n### Why LangGraph?\nUX analysis is inherently subjective. A single LLM pass tends to over-report every rough edge as a critical bug. The two-node graph separates concerns:\n\n- **Researcher node** simulates an evidence-based UX researcher mentally walking through the product as a first-time user.\n- **Critic node** acts as a design director who knows that not everything is a bug — some patterns are intentional brand or platform choices. It validates each finding, classifying it as a `genuine_bug`, `stylistic_choice`, or `needs_investigation`.\n\nThis produces a more credible, actionable output compared to a single prompt.\n\n### LangGraph State\nState uses `Annotation.Root` with explicit reducers. Both `researcherFindings` and `validatedIssues` use replacement reducers (`(_, right) => right`) since each node produces its full output in a single call. The graph streams node-level updates, allowing the API route to send progress SSE events as each node completes.\n\n### Real-time Feedback (SSE)\nThe API route uses a `ReadableStream` to emit Server-Sent Events throughout the pipeline:\n1. `uploading` → receiving file\n2. `processing` → Gemini Files API upload + polling\n3. `researching` → researcher node running\n4. `critiquing` → critic node running (fires when researcher completes)\n5. `complete` → full results payload\n\nThe frontend reads the SSE stream via `fetch` + `ReadableStream` reader, updating the progress stepper in real time.\n\n---\n\n## How to Run\n\n### Prerequisites\n- Node.js 18+\n- A Google Gemini API key (get one from [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com))\n\n### Setup\n\n```bash\ncd video_ux_analyzer\n\n# Install dependencies\nnpm install\n\n# Create your env file\ncp .env.local.example .env.local\n# Edit .env.local and add your GEMINI_API_KEY\n\n# Start the dev server\nnpm run dev\n```\n\nOpen [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000), upload a product demo video (MP4/MOV/WebM), and click **Analyze UX**.\n\n---\n\n## Production Concerns\n\n### 1. Video Upload Size & Latency\nThe current implementation uploads the video through the Next.js server (browser → Next.js → Gemini). This doubles bandwidth and hits serverless function body size limits (~4.5MB on Vercel).\n\n**Fix:** Generate a short-lived upload token server-side and have the browser upload directly to Gemini's Files API (or to an intermediary bucket like S3 with a presigned URL, then trigger processing via a background job).\n\n### 2. Serverless Timeout\nGemini video processing + two LLM calls can easily exceed 60-90 seconds for longer videos. Vercel serverless functions have a 60s default timeout (300s on Pro).\n\n**Fix:** Move processing to a background queue (e.g., BullMQ, Inngest, or a long-running container). Return a job ID immediately, poll for results, and notify via WebSocket or push notification when done.\n\n### 3. Gemini File Retention\nFiles uploaded to the Gemini Files API are automatically deleted after 48 hours. For any kind of history or re-analysis feature, the video must be stored elsewhere (e.g., S3) and re-uploaded on demand.\n\n### 4. JSON Parsing Brittleness\nBoth nodes ask Gemini to return raw JSON and use regex extraction + `JSON.parse`. Under load or with unusual video content, the model may produce malformed output.\n\n**Fix:** Use Gemini's native structured output (response schema / function calling) to enforce a JSON schema at the API level, eliminating the need for string parsing entirely.\n\n### 5. No Auth or Rate Limiting\nThe `/api/analyze` endpoint is open. Each request consumes Gemini API quota and can be expensive.\n\n**Fix:** Add authentication (NextAuth / Clerk) and per-user rate limiting (e.g., Upstash Redis).\n\n### 6. Error Recovery in the Graph\nIf the researcher node succeeds but the critic node fails, the whole analysis is lost. \n\n**Fix:** Persist intermediate node outputs (e.g., to Redis or a database keyed by job ID) so that a critic retry can resume from the saved researcher findings without re-processing the video.\n\n### 7. Prompt Versioning\nPrompts are hardcoded in the node files. Changes to prompts in production would require a deployment.\n\n**Fix:** Store prompts in a database or CMS with versioning, enabling A/B testing of researcher vs. critic personas without code deploys.\n","userModified":false},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"51436d8d-bb3d-41c5-b87a-da32cb512a68","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"/home/akshay/projects/video_ux_analyzer","sessionId":"43aa6f4e-238a-49ff-bcee-676bf9b5ead2","version":"2.1.120","gitBranch":"HEAD"}
